body:
Running with `--trace` on a low activity testcase results in a segmentation fault in `VerilatedVcd::emitTimeChange`. Encountered this issue upgrading from v5.032 -> v5.036 and bisected to [this](https://github.com/verilator/verilator/commit/34a760b75b08370aa884cb6ba297abf67cdc78bb) commit. 

Tracked down the issue to the following sequence of events:
1. Call into `VerilatedVcd::emitTimeChange(timeui=N)`
2. Printing the timestamp causes `VerilatedVcd::bufferFlush()` which nulls the `m_wrTimeBeginp` and `m_wrTimeEndp` pointers
3. `m_wrTimeEndp = m_writep` on the way out of `VerilatedVcd::emitTimeChange(timeui=N)`
4. \<no traced activity\>
5. Call into `VerilatedVcd::emitTimeChange(timeui=N+1)` and assign write pointer to nullptr (`m_writep = m_wrTimeBeginp`)
6. Segfault on trying to print "#"

One obvious solution is to add a nullptr check to specifically handle the buffer flush case:
```diff
void VerilatedVcd::emitTimeChange(uint64_t timeui) {
    // Remember pointers when last emitted time stamp; if last output was
    // timestamp backup and overwrite it.
    // This is faster then checking on every signal change if time needs to
    // be emitted.  Note buffer flushes may still emit a rare duplicate.
-  if (m_wrTimeEndp == m_writep) m_writep = m_wrTimeBeginp;
+  if (m_wrTimeEndp == m_writep) m_writep = m_wrTimeBeginp ? m_wrTimeBeginp : m_writep;
    m_wrTimeBeginp = m_writep;
    {
        printStr("#");        printStr("#");
        const std::string str = std::to_string(timeui);
        printStr(str.c_str());        printStr(str.c_str());
        printStr("\n");        printStr("\n");
    }
    m_wrTimeEndp = m_writep;
}
```

I'm using closed source HDL/testbench that I can't share so I don't have a minimal reproduction. FWIW I haven't seen the issue since adding the above patch locally. Open to suggestions on the best way to generate/modify a testcase for this.

